title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield Arms M6 Scout Survival Rifle .22LR/410ga O/U
postcontent:
When you talk about a true “Survival Rifle” you enter an entirely different realm. One of the icons of this class of weapon is the Springfield Armory M6 Scout Survival Rifle. 

The Springfield M6 Scout covers a variety of needs in both normal and emergency situations. Improved and updated from the original U.S. Air Force M6 Survival Rifle, the Springfield M6 Scout is a tough, reliable rifle you can depend on. 

Minimal moving parts 
Extreme durability 
Simple operation 
Exceptionally Reliable

The M6 was a standard component of survival kits for Air Force aircrews beginning in the 1950s through the early 1970s. The upper barrel is chambered for a .22LR round. The lower barrel is chambered for a 3" .410 shotgun shell. 

The hammer is manually cocked, the barrel is manually selected and an oversized trigger accommodates easy firing – even with a gloved hand. 

An ammo magazine built into the stock, and secured by a locking cover, holds an emergency supply of .410 shells (4) and .22 cartridges (15). 

The M6 Scout features a folding stock which is easily detached via a quick-release pivot pin. An M6 breaks down in less than 5 seconds to a very compact overall length of 18", providing easy storage on a boat, small plane, tractor or recreational vehicle (check local laws regarding storage). A specially designed trigger guard allows conventional finger firing, or full hand firing while wearing mittens or heavy gloves and weighs about 4lbs. 

This one is in very good condition. I do not have a case for it but they are available online at http://www.bodermansports.com/Firearms/Springfield_Armory/M6_Scout/m6_scout.html .

If you are looking for a survival weapon, the M6 should be at the top of your list!

Asking $650 or best reasonable cash offer.  Call/Text 5O5 six-Ten fifty-two 91

title: For Sale/Trade:  K98k Scoped
postcontent:
Barrel dated 1936, and in its original 8mm Mauser caliber, this ww2 rifle is ready to relive its live as a war time weapon with a reenacter, collector or big game hunter.

Made with the strong Mauser 1898 action, this is a very rugged and trialed by fire weapon. This rifle sports a C.P. Goerz Berlin 6x Scope, with brass hardware. It is mounted to the rifle by the way of claw mounting which requires no re zero after attaching and detaching the scope, as long as your adjustments on the knob weren't touched its good to go.

Live fired only a handful of times by myself its pretty accurate and superbly scoped by the original builder. Great groups at 100 yards, and I'm pretty sure you could take her out further but I have no long distance place too shoot at ;)

It's been my reenacting rifle for about 5 years now and it is taken care of, but sports a ding on the bell from being dropped or knocked into something. It's purely cosmetic and is hardly noticeable unless staring down the rifle from the front. It does NOT effect the scope's visibility or anything else. Scope is also pitted, but it was made in 1910 and I don't know what people expect from a scope thats 100 years old and survived both world wars....

It is a waffenampt rifle and so are most of its parts, and the stock has a flat butt plate as per early pattern regs. NICE Waffen marked stock with H for HEER or Army. Has a non-catching mag plate so you can open and close the bolt without having to hold down the floor plate, as per early war reg. Comes with reproduction sling for a 98k mauser, and cleaning rod (original).

I'm really needing the cash too fix my truck, but I can take trades, $1000 or Best Offer
